2) whose intricate aesthetics pass perceptive critique on concurrent political-economic discourses and their subtle reconfiguration of race, class, and gender. The speculative near-future scenarios projected by these artifacts expose the rise of risk as a new rationality of governance. At the same time they illustrate neoliberal speculation as a new paradigm of subject formation at a hyper-capitalist, millennial Pacific Rim.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAmerican fictionxThemes, motives. 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aRisk in literature. 0aSpeculationxIn literature. 4aAmerica. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aBigelow. 4aBritish Studies. 4aCultural Studies. 4aLai. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aLiterature. 4aNeoliberalism. 4aPacific Rim. 4aRisk and Speculation. 4aYamashita. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aAmerica.  aAmerican Studies.  aBigelow.  aBritish Studies.  aCultural Studies.  aLai.  aLiterary Studies.  aLiterature.  aNeoliberalism.  aPacific Rim.  aRisk and Speculation.  aYamashita.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyterttranscript Backlist eBook Package 2000-2013z978311102523008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyterttranscript English Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066155208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyterttranscript Highlight Collection Complete Package 2010-2013z9783110352856oZDB-23-TSO08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyterttranscript Highlight Collection Lit. & Kultur 2010-2013z978311037074408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyterttranscript: Complete eBook-Package 2013z9783110401219oZDB-23-TGP0 cprintz978383762416840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/transcript.9783839424162?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783839424162423Coveruhttps://www.deg